
RBAC → Controls who can do what in Kubernetes (authorization system)

ServiceAccount → Creates an identity for applications (pods) to access cluster

Role → Defines permissions for resources inside a specific namespace

RoleBinding → Assigns a Role to users or ServiceAccounts in a namespace

ClusterRole → Defines permissions at cluster level (all namespaces)

ClusterRoleBinding → Assigns ClusterRole to users or ServiceAccounts across cluster

ResourceQuota → Limits total resource usage (CPU, memory, pods) in a namespace

LimitRange → Sets default and max/min resource limits per container/pod

NetworkPolicy → Controls network traffic between pods (allow/deny communication)

PodDisruptionBudget → Ensures minimum pods stay running during voluntary disruptions

ServiceAccount in Kubernetes
A ServiceAccount is an identity used by Pods to communicate with the Kubernetes API.
It is commonly used with RBAC (Roles and RoleBindings) to grant specific permissions to workloads running inside the cluster.
